    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/1758¾</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">14 May, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I was as sorry as you can have
                    been to withdraw the “statement” which we had intended for the press.<note
                        n="61" xml:id="d360fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_402">p. 402</ref>.</note> It
                    cost me a struggle to do so. But the intimation was plain from the German
                    Embassy (and I cannot doubt the source of my information) that we were not in
                    earnest, would speak only in a Pickwickian sense if we seemed to speak with
                    firmness, and I did not dare lend colour to that impression. You will notice
                    that hope of a pacific settlement was expressed. That, in the circumstances, was
                    as far as I dared to go.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
